<h1>Lee Jung Seop Arts District, Seogwipo</h1>
<p>After the waterfalls, we drove through Seogwipo, one of the largest cities on the island. There are parts of this city which are very new, urban, and modern, with heavy traffic, street food, Gangnam-style shopping, and high-rise apartments. For our first stop, we explored the tiny hidden treasure that's tucked inside the hilly streets of Seogwipo - a special art-district-street dedicated to Korean artist, Lee Jeong-Sup. Apparently, his tragic life story has made him quite the legend on the island, which includes a museum, shops, and restaurants named after him. Outside Lee's house, there's a storyteller-ahjumma that does an amazing job narrating his life story, but no English interpreter available. You have to park at least a couple blocks away, but it is definitely worth checking out.</p>
